What is the difference between:
Docker Image
Docker Container
Docker Layer
Explain how they relate internally.

Solution:-
🔹 Docker Image

Immutable template

Read-only

Built from Dockerfile

Composed of layers

It is NOT a stopped container.

🔹 Docker Container

Runtime instance of image

Adds writable layer on top

Has:

Namespaces

Cgroups

Network interface

PID 1 process

Image = Blueprint
Container = Running house built from blueprint

🔹 Docker Layers

Each Dockerfile instruction:

RUN

COPY

ADD

Creates a new filesystem layer.

Docker uses OverlayFS:

Layer 1
Layer 2
Layer 3
-------------
Writable layer (container)

Layers are:

Immutable

Cached

Shared across images

This is why:
Multiple containers can use same image efficiently.
